Hydrochar exhibits unique physical, chemical, and biological properties, including a high specific surface area and pore volume, high mineral content, enhanced surface functional groups, long-term stability, etc. (Fig. 1
                     ) [14–17]. Owing to their physicochemical properties, several articles have summarized the application of food waste hydrochar (FWH) in multiple fields to address various SDGs such as adsorbent in the treatment of polluted water (SDG 6.3: improve water quality, wastewater treatment and safe reuse) [18–21], as a solid fuel and in electrochemical devices to generate clean energy (SDG 7: affordable and clean energy) [8,22–24], as a CO2 remover to contribute to the fight against climate change (SDG 13: combat climate change) [25–28], as a soil quality improver to aid in the land restoration (SDG 15.3: end desertification and restore degraded land), and increase agricultural productivity, thereby addressing hunger (SDG 2: zero hunger) [29,30]. Moreover, the United Nations established 17 SDGs for 2030, with 169 associated targets in September 2015, and 193 nations endorsed this initiative to foster global improvements and enhance the quality of life [1]. It has been more than eight years since then, and significant work still needs to be accomplished to reach the stated objectives (Fig. 2
                     ). Moreover, compared to biochar, FWH is still in the early stages in terms of optimization of production processes custom design for specific applications due to limited porosity, surface area and functional groups [5,15,17].
